headline: CNN This Morning
subHeadline: Nets Blow up Team; Donna Kelce is Interviewed about the Super Bowl. Aired 8:30-9a ET

utterances.speaker: DON LEMON, CNN ANCHOR
utterances.sentences: OK, so -- let's get -- we're talking about NBA trade deadlines. There's a lot of trading going on. So, look, I want to get right to it. The Nets have traded Kevin Durant to the Phoenix Suns. That happened overnight. Comes right after Kyrie Irving says he's going away to the Dallas Mavericks. Official end to what they thought was a very promising super team over in Brooklyn.LZ Granderson is here. He is a columnist at "The Los Angeles Times," host of the podcast "Life Outloud." LZ, thank you. So, what do you make, the end of this - it was supposed to be a super team. What up? What happened? LZ GRANDERSON, OP-ED COLUMNIST, "LOS ANGELES TIMES": You know, this is the part of construction of NBA rosters that people forget about, that it takes more than just talent in order to build a championship. You've got to have cohesion. You've got to have some luck. You've got to have clarity from the ownership group all the way down to the 12th man on the team. And the Brooklyn Nets just never had that. You went through all the players that were traded. But, remember, before that, James Harden was traded the year before. And before James Harden was traded, remember, they also -- they also fired Steve Nash, their head coach. And so this is the franchise that has started to disintegrate almost as soon as it was put together.

utterances.speaker: GRANDERSON
utterances.sentences: Well, you know, that's a -- it's a fascinating question because all of that has to do with, what is Kyrie's ultimate goal, right? He is going to be a free agent this year, which means he has to kind of play the good soldier publicly if he wants to sign a long-term deal, either with the Mavericks or some other team. And so I think both the Dallas Mavericks, as well as Kyrie, have a lot invested in order to try to make this work. Kyrie is certainly wanting to secure his - his financial future and the Dallas Mavericks want to return as winners with Luka Doncic.So, I think you're going to see Kyrie on his best behavior. But then again, I said that when he was in Boston, and I said that when he was in Brooklyn, too, so what do I know?

utterances.speaker: KAITLAN COLLINS, CNN ANCHOR
utterances.sentences: Yes, but it does - it does -- well, hey, we think you know a lot. That's why we're having you on.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: But it does brings -- it's going to put a lot of focus on this and what he does do next. Probably even more focus than was already on him.Yes. Yes. Absolutely. And, you know, the deleted post, we don't know when he deleted it, so I don't want to necessarily assume that the trade and the deletion of the posts are connected. But he had to know that there would be a response to deleting that post. So right there lets you know that even though he may be a good soldier, he's not going to not be Kyrie. And so it's going to be interesting to see how he threads the needle between being who he always has been and being what he needs to be in order to secure that bag.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Yes. It's a great point. He said, I want to be in places I'm celebrated, not just kind of tolerated.LZ, thank you, friend. We'll have you back for longer next time. We appreciate it.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: And secure that bag, LZ. All right.

utterances.speaker: GRANDERSON
utterances.sentences: Thank you for having me. Yes, keep that bag, baby.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: A sibling -

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Thank you.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: A sibling rivalry on football's biggest stage. We talk to Travis and Jason Kelce's mom about Sunday's historic matchup and which son she'll be cheering for.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Tough call.(BEGIN VIDEO CLIP)

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: How on earth do you decide who to root for?

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Well, there will be more than a Super Bowl on the line when the Philadelphia Eagles and Kansas City Chiefs square off in Arizona this weekend. It will also be a battle for family bragging rights like we have never seen before. Jason Kelce, a star offensive lineman for the Eagles, and Travis Kelce, a star tight end for the Chiefs, set to become the very first brothers ever to face off in a Super Bowl. The standout siblings played together in high school and college and now they'll line up on opposite sides of the field on the NFL's big stage. The brothers kicked off the week with a special surprise from their mother, Donna, who crashed an interview to surprise her boys with, what else, homemade cookies.I got to talk to her yesterday. (BEGIN VIDEOTAPE)

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: All right, how on earth do you decide who to root for?

utterances.speaker: DONNA KELCE, SONS WILL BE FIRST PAIR OF BROTHERS TO FACE OFF IN SUPER BOWL
utterances.sentences: Oh, it's going to be easy. You know, I have to stand and scream the entire game. They're both on offense. So, every time somebody has the ball, I'll be clapping. And every time somebody gets a touchdown, I'll be thrilled. So, it will be great. It's going to be just fun.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: There you go. There you go. I love it.I have to ask, because every parent watching this is going to want to know what on earth you did to have two sons so fit to make it to the Super Bowl.

utterances.speaker: KELCE
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: What did you feed these guys? KELCEyou know, you -- when they're into sports and they did everything, they played every kind of possible sport you could think of, baseball, a lot of tournaments. We were constantly on the road. You're grabbing, you know, like fast food. I wasn't perfect at that point. Making sure that they had, you know, nutritious meals. I did the best I could.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: KELCE
utterances.sentences: But basically, you know, it was a lot of protein and they just, you know, they ate a lot. It was a lot. A lot of food. And constantly.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: I - I can - I can only imagine that you would fill the fridge and then it would be completely empty like two days later.How much trash-talk, Donna, at the dinner table?

utterances.speaker: KELCE
utterances.sentences: Oh, there wasn't that much because they were on the same team.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Well, there you go.

utterances.speaker: KELCE
utterances.sentences: But they were -- there was a lot of bickering. A lot of bickering and a lot of, you know, one-upping and who won, you know, who can get to the table first, who could get to the car first. You know, to ride in the front seat. It's just - it's just things like that. Constantly competing. And I think that's what really drove both of them to be the way that they are. It's just the need and the want to beat somebody in their house and they're both very athletic. So they had the best, you know, individuals to practice against right at home.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Yes, that's true.On a more serious note, because not only do they have this big game match-off together.

utterances.speaker: KELCE
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: KELCE
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: What did you do?

utterances.speaker: KELCE
utterances.sentences: Well, yes. You know, there's a true story. Jason did not get any scholarships to go to college. And I said, you know, I believe in you. You believe in yourself. Just persevere. Keep doing it. I know you have it within you. Just try your hardest. Don't give up. You'll never forgive yourself. Pick a school. We'll work it out. We'll find a way that we can make it work. And that's exactly what he did.And the same thing with Travis. I mean, he's had his own adversity with different things and I would tell him the same thing. If this is something you truly, truly love to do, keep at it. Ask them, how can I get more playing time? What can I do? How can I get better? But it's got to come from the kid, not the parent.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Yes. Yes, that's true, right, it's something in them that helps them keep going.

utterances.speaker: KELCE
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: But I think moms and dads have a lot to do with it.

utterances.speaker: KELCE
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Both of them were drafted by Kansas City Chiefs head coach Andy Reid. And he was asked this week about them. And I love what he said. He called them both compassionate competitors who care about people as much as they care about the game.

utterances.speaker: KELCE
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: You know, eventually the sport ends, right? And eventually you're not playing in the NFL anymore.

utterances.speaker: KELCE
utterances.sentences: Correct.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: You're who you are as a person.

utterances.speaker: KELCE
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: So what did that mean to you to hear that?

utterances.speaker: KELCE
utterances.sentences: You know, I -- that makes a mom feel like she did something right. Sports is a game. And it's fun. And if you get to play it, it's amazing. But not all - not everyone can get there. I mean, you know, things have to happen the right time, the right coaches. Teams have to need your skill set. So, you know, you need to do something after sports. It's a very, very fleeting career. Even though they've been doing it for over ten years, that's surprising, too.But you need to treat everyone with respect and kindness and just treat, you know, don't make yourself better than anyone else because that is just -- it's important to have a good character. And that will see you through anything.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Amen.All right, I got to ask, what do you say to the son whose team doesn't go home with the trophy?

utterances.speaker: KELCE
utterances.sentences: Yes. Yes. Yes, that's a tough one. It's going to be hard because in -- you know, when somebody wins, only the winners and the winners' families are allowed on the field. The losers have to leave, you know? HARLOW

utterances.speaker: KELCE
utterances.sentences: They go off the field. So, I can't see them. They're going to get on a bus and they're going to go to their hotel. And there will be post-parties for both, the winners and the losers, because it was a rough year. And I will go to the post-game hotel after the ceremony and I will give my son a huge hug and a kiss because there's nothing that I could say that will, you know, mean anything at that point. He's going to be a broken, you know, person.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Yes. Yes.

utterances.speaker: KELCE
utterances.sentences: So, you know, he'll be happy for his brother, but, you know, the hours and the months that you put in to get it this point, it's tough.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Well, from one mom to the next, to you, the hours that you put in to raising them, look at where they have come.Donna Kelce, what a treat - what a treat to get to talk to you. Have a lot of fun.

utterances.speaker: KELCE
utterances.sentences: Oh, (INAUDIBLE). Thanks.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: And I'll root for the offense with you, OK?

utterances.speaker: KELCE
utterances.sentences: There you go. That's good.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: There you go.

utterances.speaker: KELCE
utterances.sentences: Yes, it will be fun.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: OK.

utterances.speaker: KELCE
utterances.sentences: Let's hope for a high-scoring game.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: There you go.Donna Kelce, congrats.

utterances.speaker: KELCE
utterances.sentences: All right. OK, thank you so much.(END VIDEOTAPE)

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: She's my new favorite American mama after my own. She's so great.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Poppy, she's so cute.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: And the back of her jersey is the Eagles. The front is the Chiefs.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Split.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: And her tennis shoes are split. And her jacket is split. COLLINSand games, they played every sport, feeding them, you know, fast food. She was saying, it wasn't always the most nutritious.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: She made me feel better, yes.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: So -

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: But every parent, you know, everyone -- my brother has played so many sports. And you drive them every - you do all these things. And like it shows that, like, it's worth it.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: My kids are going to take the subway in the city.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Here's my - here's my question.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Which party would you go to?

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Well, no, I know, because you told me during the piece.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Which party would you go to?

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: I'm going to go to the winners' party.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Maybe the loser. Maybe I'm with you.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: I would go -- I would go to the losers party because he's going to have so much support from the winner's party.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: No, you'd be such a good dad. It's true.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: But - and, look, I'm not a mom. You would go to - I guess, you're right. I never thought about that.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: You do both.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Yes, she's going to go to both things or whatever.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: But the first one I'd go to is the loser party.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Wait, do they have a loser party?

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: She said - yes, she -- according to her, she said yes.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: OK.So, Donna, come back on Monday, OK?

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: I don't think we should have a loser party.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: I'm not going to be here, but come back and talk to these guys on Monday after one of your sons wins the Super Bowl, OK?

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: She was - that was best moment of the show. HARLOW

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: You go to both. Here's the thing.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: What?

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: They are -- they are all winners, especially the mom because - and she did a great job raising good kids.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: And the - and the dad, too.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: And the dad.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: We didn't see him, but, yes, of course, that goes -

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Yes, both of them.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: OK. That was fun.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Really?

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Some people might find it hard to believe, but some lawmakers are actually funny sometimes. Lawmakers from both sides of the aisle let loose at the Washington Press Club Foundation's annual congressional dinner last night. Don's a little skeptical about their humor, but they shared a lot of laughs as they roasted each other and sometimes themselves.(BEGIN VIDEO CLIP) REP. NANCY MACE (R-SC): Did you watch the - did you watch McCarthy during the speaker's vote. I know many of you were in the halls of Congress during that vote. I haven't seen someone assume that many positions to appease the crazy Republicans since Stormy Daniels. SEN. CHUCK SCHUMER (D-NY): Now, admittedly, I was -- I wasn't sure whether I'd be able to make it tonight, but my staff reminded me that hundreds, hundreds of reporters were attending this event, and magically my schedule cleared right up.

utterances.speaker: MACE
utterances.sentences: And I know everyone thinks Republicans aren't funny. But if you get a bunch of us together, we can be a real riot.SEN. RAPHAEL WARNOCK (D-GA): And thanks again for having me with you tonight. If you like my remarks, my name is Raphael Warnock. If you didn't, I'm Senator Tim Scott. Good night, everybody. (END VIDEO CLIP)

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: So, have you changed your mind?

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Not really. It was good.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Well, you know, Maxwell Frost, that 25-year-old congressman, Nancy Mace said she had stretch marks that were older than she was.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: So funny.OK.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: That dress --

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Was beautiful.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Yes, that was quite a dress. (INAUDIBLE).

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: CNN "NEWSROOM."

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: All right. Thanks for joining us this morning. We have no more jokes here. So, we'll let you go.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: For now.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Right after this break.
